QBATCH(1)               User   Contributed   Perl   Documentation
QBATCH(1)



NNAAMMEE
       qbatch - submits a command line to Grid Engine or PBS  via
qsub

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       qqbbaattcchh [options] [--qq queue] -- command

       qbatch  is designed to be inserted before any command that
you would
       usually run from the command line.  In  case  of  argument
collision where
       both  your  command  and  qbatch  share  an option such as
--verbose be sure
       to use the '--' syntax to split qbatch  options  from  the
commands
       options

          $ qbatch --verbose -- mincmath --verbose ...

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       qqbbaattcchh  is  a quick hack if you don't want to write a qqssuubb
script

       The idea is to just bung qqbbaattcchh in front  of  any  command
you would
       normally enter on the command line. (as per 'nice')

        eg:
           $ qbatch ls -F
           $  qbatch  -q  wb325.q@taylor  -N  job23  --  mincmath
fred.mnc ..

       Problems or comments should be sent to: a.janke@gmail.com

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --vv, ----vveerrbboossee
           Be noisy when doing things (most importantly this will
echo the
           resulting script to the terminal)

       ----vveerrssiioonn
           Print version number and exit

       --hh, ----hheellpp
           Dump some quick help output

       ----mmaann
           Dump a man page

       --ff, ----ffaakkee
           Don't  run anything, This is useful when combined with
--verbose or
           --script

       --ss, ----ssccrriipptt
           Dont run anything, just output the batch script to the
specified
           filename

       ----ttyyppee
           Type  of  queing  system,  currently only pbs and gri-
dengine are
           supported

       --qq, ----qquueeuuee
           Specify a queue to run a job in.  Use  something  like
all.q@hostname
           to  specify a particular host.  Defaults to all.q, the
default SGE
           queue

       --NN, ----nnaammee
           Specify a job name to run the job as. By default  this
will be
           "STDIN"

       --dd, ----ddeeppeennddss
           Specify a list of job dependencies by job name or num-
ber which have
           to run before this job will

       --ll, ----llooggffiillee
           Logfile for output of the  command.  By  Default  this
will make a file
           in the current directory called qbatch-<PID>.log where
PID is the
           Process ID of the instance of qbatch

       --jj, ----jjiidd
           return only the job id of the submitted job on STDOUT

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       _q_s_u_b(1) _q_d_e_l(1)

AAUUTTHHOORR
       Andrew Janke - a.janke@gmail.com



